# RDF 3.0.7 Release Notes

## Context-Efficient Reads Release

Three changes that target the single biggest source of wasted tokens
in long-running RDF sessions: full-file reads of large source files
when the agent only needs one symbol.

**`/r-util-code-map` slash command.** Structural map of a source
file — classes, functions, methods with per-symbol line ranges.
Inspired by GitHub issue anthropics/claude-code#34304 (measured
80% context reduction on a 6-file call-chain trace). Language
dispatch covers Python (via the `ast` module, high fidelity),
shell (awk-based function extraction, medium fidelity), TypeScript
/ JavaScript (ctags preferred, grep fallback), Go, Rust, C/C++,
Ruby, with tree-sitter preferred when the binary is installed.
Threshold is configurable per project via
`governance/conventions.md:code-map-threshold` (default 500
lines). The skill is composable: other skills and agents invoke
it before reading large files.

**`/r-util-code-scan` wired into `/r-audit` as baseline.** A new
Stage 1c runs the full pattern-class scan up front and writes the
results to `.rdf/work-output/audit-baseline-patterns.md`. Stage 2
subagents receive the baseline as extra context rather than
re-deriving the same grep matches. UNTRACKED pattern hits are
promoted to formal findings by the regression/anti-slop reviewer;
TRACKED hits pass through unless the reviewer identifies new
context. `--quick` mode now uses `/r-util-code-scan all` as its
canonical anti-pattern check, replacing the previous ad-hoc
`grep governance/anti-patterns.md` pass.

**Anti-pattern drift delta in `/r-refresh`.** A new Stage 1d
compares the current `/r-util-code-scan all` counts against a
snapshot at `.rdf/governance/.scan-baseline.json` and surfaces
only the delta — one summary line in Drift Detection listing each
pattern class whose count changed, sign-prefixed. No findings
table in refresh output; users follow up with
`/r-util-code-scan <class>` for detail. Skipped for `state` and
`github` scopes. First-run behavior creates the baseline without
emitting a delta.

**Why this shape.** The code-map skill is the primitive; `/r-audit`
and `/r-refresh` are its first consumers. Large-file discipline
(code-map before Read) is also written into the reviewer dispatch
payload in Stage 2a so subagents in the audit pipeline inherit
the same efficiency behavior. The refresh delta is intentionally
narrow — snapshot-based, counts-only, one line — because full
findings tables belong in `/r-audit`, and refresh should remain
a cheap drift-sync step.

**Consumers.** Projects that update to 3.0.7 gain:

- A faster `/r-audit` that doesn't redo grep work across subagents
- `/r-refresh` tracking whether codebase hygiene is improving or
  regressing between governance syncs
- A reusable primitive (`/r-util-code-map`) that downstream utility
  skills can compose on (`/r-util-test-scope`, `/r-util-doc-gen`,
  `/r-util-code-scan` can all narrow their own work with it)

**File changes.**

- `canonical/commands/r-util-code-map.md` (new)
- `canonical/commands/r-audit.md` (Stage 1c, Stage 2a, `--quick`)
- `canonical/commands/r-refresh.md` (Stage 1d, Stage 6c)
- `README.md` (utility table, counts)
- `RDF.md` (tree layout, counts)
- `CHANGELOG`, `CHANGELOG.RELEASE`, `VERSION`

**Command count:** 34 → 35. Utility commands: 14 → 15.

